This problem looks like another great use for Monte Carlo simulation (when you have a hammer, every problem starts to look like a nail... ). I ran a simulation based on the volatility (getting data for this simulation was a pain, does anyone know of a good data source?). The market is turbulent, but there isn't a lot of time left for this question, so it seems pretty likely that we'll remain in the "More than $2.5 trillion" bucket. The crowd looks pretty much aligned to my simulation results. There might be good reasons to think the market will do something different than the simulation results forecast, but it seems to be a reasonable "outside view". { "Less than $1.0 trillion": 0.01%, "Between $1.0 trillion and $1.5 trillion, inclusive": 0.25%, "More than $1.5 trillion but less than $2.0 trillion": 3.75%, "Between $2.0 trillion and $2.5 trillion, inclusive": 17.55%, "More than $2.5 trillion": 78.44%, } CODE: https://github.com/jonathanmann/gjopen/tree/master/coin_cap ENGINE: https://github.com/jonathanmann/gjopen/blob/master/monte_carlo_forecasting/MonteCarlo.py
